<dl id="n08183d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08183d">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08183d"> 183(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Scotti 1<sup>ier</sup> 1<sup>st</sup> Ir G<font color="green">[u]</font>ards</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">That is one of the secrets of Patrick s success. Another is the prestige of Rome. The Irish, though they lay outside the Roman world, were in contact with it, and the first &ldquo;Irish Brigade&rdquo; that ever existed served in Roman armies. We hear in the fourth century of the <i>Scotti Primi</i> (First Irish Guards), as also of regiments of the Atecotti, who are thought to be bodies drawn from the non-Gaelic military tribes. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 25-26</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
